"# Chapter 15 — Peter Landin

Peter John Landin. Born 1930 in Sheffield, England. Died 2009 in
London. British computer scientist. Worked at the University of
London, mostly at Queen Mary College.

He connected the lambda calculus to programming languages in a way
that changed how the field thought. He invented the SECD machine,
one of the first models of how to actually implement a functional
language. He wrote a paper called *The Next 700 Programming
Languages* that argued the field had already found the important
ideas and just needed to package them in different syntax.

Less well-known outside academia than some of his peers. Deeply
respected inside it.

## The SECD machine

In 1964 Landin published *The Mechanical Evaluation of Expressions*.
In it he described a virtual machine — the SECD machine — that
evaluates lambda-calculus expressions using four stacks:

- **S** — the operand stack
- **E** — the environment (bindings of variables to values)
- **C** — the code (the expression being evaluated)
- **D** — the dump (saved states, for returning from function calls)

The SECD machine was one of the first models of how you could
actually run a functional program on a real computer. Every
subsequent virtual machine for functional languages — the CAM,
the STG machine (used by GHC for Haskell), the ZINC machine (used
by early OCaml), the JVM's variant handling — draws from Landin's
design.

## The Next 700 Programming Languages

In 1966 Landin published *The Next 700 Programming Languages*. The
title was a joke about how many programming languages had appeared
in the previous decade. His argument: nearly all of them were
variations on a small number of core ideas. If you understood the
lambda calculus and a few conveniences on top, you understood
almost every language people were building.

He proposed a language he called ISWIM — 'If you See What I Mean'
— as a template. ISWIM had:
- Lambda expressions
- `let` and `where` bindings
- Layout-based syntax (indentation matters)
- Infix operators for readability

ISWIM was never widely implemented as a shipping language. But its
descendants are numerous. ML, Haskell, and later Python and Ruby all
borrow layout-based syntax and the general shape of Landin's ISWIM.

## Call-by-name, call-by-value, call-by-need

Landin's work formalized the distinction between different ways a
programming language can pass arguments. In call-by-value, the
argument is evaluated once, before the function starts. In
call-by-name, the argument is evaluated every time it's used inside
the function. In call-by-need (thunks with memoization), the
argument is evaluated on demand, at most once, and cached.

Different languages pick different strategies. Motoi Scheme uses
call-by-value by default; explicit thunks give you call-by-need if
you want it. Landin's framework is where the vocabulary comes from.

## The J operator

Landin introduced an operator called J that captured the notion of
a saved continuation. Later Scheme and other languages formalized
this as `call/cc` — the ability to grab the current continuation as
a first-class value. Not every kid needs to know `call/cc` exists.
But it exists because Landin thought about the shape of program
control forty years before it became standard.

## What Motoi owes Landin

The connection between the lambda calculus and programming
languages. The idea that most programming languages are re-skinning
of the same small set of computational ideas. The SECD-family of
virtual machines from which functional-language runtimes descend.
Call-by-value vs. call-by-name as a first-class distinction.

## A tiny example

Simulating a SECD-style evaluation of a simple expression in Motoi
Scheme. This isn't the real SECD, but the shape is right:

```
(define (secd-eval code env)
  (let loop ((s '())      ;; operand stack
             (e env)      ;; environment
             (c code)     ;; code
             (d '()))     ;; dump
    (cond
      ((null? c)
       (car s))           ;; final result on top of stack
      ((pair? (car c))
       ;; nested expression: evaluate it recursively
       (loop
         (cons (secd-eval (car c) e) s)
         e (cdr c) d))
      (else
       (case (car c)
         ((push)
          (loop (cons (cadr c) s) e (cddr c) d))
         ((add)
          (let ((a (car s)) (b (cadr s)))
            (loop (cons (+ a b) (cddr s))
                  e (cdr c) d)))
         ((mul)
          (let ((a (car s)) (b (cadr s)))
            (loop (cons (* a b) (cddr s))
                  e (cdr c) d)))
         (else
          (loop s e (cdr c) d)))))))

(secd-eval '(push 3 push 4 add) '())   ;; => 7
(secd-eval '(push 5 push 6 mul) '())   ;; => 30
```

Compact. Landin's insight: an interpreter is a state-machine you can
formalize and reason about. Every modern language runtime is built
on this insight.

## Where to read him

*Mechanical Evaluation of Expressions* (Landin, 1964). *The Next 700
Programming Languages* (Landin, 1966, in *Communications of the
ACM*). His work is technical but accessible; the *Next 700* paper is
readable in an evening.

## Motoi's take

Landin looked at a proliferation of programming languages and saw
one underlying pattern. That's the kind of taste that saves the
next generation years of confusion. Motoi Scheme lives inside the
family Landin outlined.")
